<Link id="l00024" /><CodeLine lineNumber="24"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Calculate and dump ThinLTO specific inliner stats.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00025" /><CodeLine lineNumber="25"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The main statistics are:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00026" /><CodeLine lineNumber="26"><Highlight kind="comment">/// (1) Number of inlined imported functions,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00027" /><CodeLine lineNumber="27"><Highlight kind="comment">/// (2) Number of imported functions inlined into importing module (indirect),</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00028" /><CodeLine lineNumber="28"><Highlight kind="comment">/// (3) Number of non imported functions inlined into importing module</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00029" /><CodeLine lineNumber="29"><Highlight kind="comment">/// (indirect).</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00030" /><CodeLine lineNumber="30"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The difference between first and the second is that first stat counts</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00031" /><CodeLine lineNumber="31"><Highlight kind="comment">/// all performed inlines on imported functions, but the second one only the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00032" /><CodeLine lineNumber="32"><Highlight kind="comment">/// functions that have been eventually inlined to a function in the importing</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00033" /><CodeLine lineNumber="33"><Highlight kind="comment">/// module (by a chain of inlines). Because llvm uses bottom-up inliner, it is</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00034" /><CodeLine lineNumber="34"><Highlight kind="comment">/// possible to e.g. import function &#96;A&#96;, &#96;B&#96; and then inline &#96;B&#96; to &#96;A&#96;,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00035" /><CodeLine lineNumber="35"><Highlight kind="comment">/// and after this &#96;A&#96; might be too big to be inlined into some other function</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00036" /><CodeLine lineNumber="36"><Highlight kind="comment">/// that calls it. It calculates this statistic by building graph, where</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00037" /><CodeLine lineNumber="37"><Highlight kind="comment">/// the nodes are functions, and edges are performed inlines and then by marking</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00038" /><CodeLine lineNumber="38"><Highlight kind="comment">/// the edges starting from not imported function.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00039" /><CodeLine lineNumber="39"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00040" /><CodeLine lineNumber="40"><Highlight kind="comment">/// If &#96;Verbose&#96; is set to true, then it also dumps statistics</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00041" /><CodeLine lineNumber="41"><Highlight kind="comment">/// per each inlined function, sorted by the greatest inlines count like</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00042" /><CodeLine lineNumber="42"><Highlight kind="comment">/// - number of performed inlines</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00043" /><CodeLine lineNumber="43"><Highlight kind="comment">/// - number of performed inlines to importing module</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00044" /><CodeLine lineNumber="44" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/importedfunctionsinliningstatistics"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">class </Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"><a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/importedfunctionsinliningstatistics/#a41874db064d638d7527a03f896dad428">ImportedFunctionsInliningStatistics</a> &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
